[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sébille","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Sybil</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Sybil","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sébille de Culant was born on 21 May 1233, in Craon, Anjou, France, her father, Renoul III de Culant, was 23 and her mother, Sédille de Craon, was 20. She had at least 2 sons and 2 daughters with Eude II DE SULLY BEAUJEU. She died before 1258."},"et":{"21 May 1233–avant 1258":"21. mai 1233–enne 1258","1233–1258":"1233–1258","1240–1323":"1240–1323","1210–1258":"1210–1258","1248–1324":"1248–1324","1250–1281":"1250–1281","1252–Male":"1252–Surnud","1254–1329":"1254–1329","1210–1270":"1210–1270","1213–1276":"1213–1276","1252":"1252","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1281":"1281","21 May 1233":"21. mai 1233","Abt 1252":"umbes 1252","1248":"1248","1324":"1324","1258":"1258","1213":"1213","1323":"1323","ABT 1254":"umbes 1254","1233":"1233","1276":"1276","1254":"1254","1210":"1210","avant 1258":"enne 1258","1329":"1329","Craon, Mayenne,